# Git Workflow Rules

## Change Tracking

- Save all changes made to files in the `CHANGELOG.md` file
- Each change entry must include the date and time when the change was made
- Group changes by feature or fix
- New entries always go at the top of the file (most recent first)

## Semantic Versioning — MANDATORY on every push

Every `git push` **must** bump the project version before pushing. No exceptions.

### Rules

- Version is stored in `package.json` (`"version"` field)
- Follow [Semantic Versioning 2.0.0](https://semver.org) — `MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH`:
  - **MAJOR** (`x.0.0`) — breaking changes, incompatible API changes, schema migrations that require manual intervention
  - **MINOR** (`1.x.0`) — new features, new endpoints, new pages, significant UI additions (backward compatible)
  - **PATCH** (`1.1.x`) — bug fixes, small tweaks, hotfixes, dependency bumps, refactors with no behaviour change
- The version bump must be part of the same commit (or a dedicated `chore(release): vX.Y.Z` commit) that gets pushed
- Never push without bumping the version. If you forget, bump it and create a follow-up `chore(release)` commit before pushing

### Required steps on every push

1. Identify the type of change since the last version (major / minor / patch)
2. Update `"version"` in `package.json` accordingly
3. Add an entry to the top of `CHANGELOG.md` with:
   - Heading `## vX.Y.Z — YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM`
   - Sub-sections grouping changes (features, fixes, breaking, etc.)
4. Run `npm run build` to verify the build still passes
5. Commit the bump + changelog entry together with the feature/fix commit (or as a final `chore(release): vX.Y.Z` commit right before the push)
6. Push to remote

## Validation Before Push

- Before any `git push`, always run `npm run build`
- Only push if the build completes without errors
- Commit messages should be clear and descriptive (prefer conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`)
